Experiment 1 – Git Operations
Aim

To perform basic Git operations such as initializing a repository, committing files, creating branches, merging branches, and pushing changes to GitHub.

Description

Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in source code.
Using Git we can create repositories, manage versions, collaborate using branches, and push code to remote repositories like GitHub.

Procedure
Step 1 – Create a project folder

Create a folder for the project and open it in VS Code.

Step 2 – Initialize Git repository

Initialize Git in the project folder.

git init

This creates a .git directory which stores repository information.

Step 3 – Create a file

Create a file called README.md and add content.

# DevOps Lab
Step 4 – Add file to staging area

Add the file to Git staging area.

git add README.md
Step 5 – Commit changes

Save the changes in Git repository.

git commit -m "Initial commit"
Step 6 – Create a new branch

Create a branch for development.

git checkout -b feature
Step 7 – Create new file in branch

Create file:

hello.txt

Content:

Hello from feature branch
Step 8 – Commit branch changes
git add hello.txt
git commit -m "Added hello file"
Step 9 – Merge branch

Switch back to main branch and merge the feature branch.

git checkout main
git merge feature
Step 10 – View commit history
git log --oneline
Experiment 2 – Containerizing Flask Application using Docker
Aim

To containerize a Flask application using Docker and run it inside a container.

Description

Docker is a containerization platform that allows applications to run in isolated environments.
A Docker container includes application code, dependencies, and runtime environment.

Procedure
Step 1 – Create Flask application

Create file app.py.

from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return "Hello Docker"

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
Step 2 – Create dependency file

Create requirements.txt.

flask
Step 3 – Create Dockerfile

Create file Dockerfile.

FROM python:3.11-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt
COPY . .
EXPOSE 5000
CMD ["python","app.py"]
Step 4 – Build Docker image
docker build -t flask-app .
Step 5 – Run Docker container
docker run -d -p 5000:5000 flask-app
Step 6 – Verify output

Open browser:

http://localhost:5000

Output:

Hello Docker
Experiment 3 – Monolithic Flask Application
Aim

To develop and demonstrate a simple monolithic application using Flask.

Description

A monolithic architecture is a software design where the entire application (UI, logic, database) is developed and deployed as a single unit.

Procedure
Step 1 – Create Flask application

Create app.py.

from flask import Flask, request, jsonify

app = Flask(__name__)
students = {}

@app.route('/students', methods=['GET'])
def get_students():
    return jsonify(students)

@app.route('/students', methods=['POST'])
def add_student():
    data = request.get_json()
    students[data['roll']] = data['name']
    return jsonify(data)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
Step 2 – Install Flask
pip install flask
Step 3 – Run application
python app.py
Step 4 – Test API
http://localhost:5000/students
Experiment 4 – CI Pipeline using GitHub Actions
Aim

To create a CI pipeline using GitHub Actions to automatically build the project when code is pushed.

Description

GitHub Actions is a continuous integration tool that automates build, test, and deployment workflows.

Procedure
Step 1 – Create GitHub repository

Create a new repository in GitHub.

Step 2 – Push project to GitHub
git init
git add .
git commit -m "initial commit"
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/python-app.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
Step 3 – Create workflow folder
.github/workflows
Step 4 – Create workflow file
ci.yml
Step 5 – Add workflow code
name: CI Pipeline

on:
 push:
  branches: [ main ]

jobs:
 build:
  runs-on: ubuntu-latest

  steps:
   - uses: actions/checkout@v3
   - run: echo "CI Pipeline Running"
Step 6 – Push workflow
git add .
git commit -m "Added CI pipeline"
git push
Step 7 – Verify pipeline

Open GitHub → Actions tab.

